04792nam a22006855i 9781478012979DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780129797 a10.1515/97814780129792doi  a(DE-B1597)577370  a(OCoLC)1227041548  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a320.082/09521 aSchieder, Chelsea Szendi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCoed Revolution :bThe Female Student in the Japanese New Left /cChelsea Szendi Schieder. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society : 4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Gendering the Japanese New Left -- t1. Naive Politics: A Maiden Sacrifice for Postwar Democracy -- t2. “ My Love and Rebellion”: The Politics of Nurturing, the Logic of Capital, and the Rationalization of Coeducation -- t3. Is the Personal Political? Everyday Life as a Site of Struggle in the Campus New Left -- t4. “ When You Fuck a Vanguard Girl . . . ”: The Spectacle of New Left Masculinity -- t5. “ Gewalt Rosas”: The Creation of the Terrifying, Titillating Female Student Activist -- tConclusion: Revolutionary Desire -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the 1960s, a new generation of university-educated youth in Japan challenged forms of capitalism and the state. In Coed Revolution Chelsea Szendi Schieder recounts the crucial stories of Japanese women's participation in these protest movements led by the New Left through the early 1970s. Women were involved in contentious politics to an unprecedented degree, but they and their concerns were frequently marginalized by men in the movement and the mass media, and the movement at large is often memorialized as male and masculine. Drawing on stories of individual women, Schieder outlines how the media and other activists portrayed these women as icons of vulnerability and victims of violence, making women central to discourses about legitimate forms of postwar political expression. Schieder disentangles the gendered patterns that obscured radical women's voices to construct a feminist genealogy of the Japanese New Left, demonstrating that student activism in 1960s Japan cannot be understood without considering the experiences and representations of these women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCivil societyzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and culturezJapany20th century. 0aSocial movementszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aStudentsxPolitical activityzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzJapan. 0aWomen's rightszJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478012979?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478012979423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478012979/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishb2021  a